        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Topic clustering best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>One keyword per page, always.</strong> Each cluster page targets one primary keyword. Cluster pages that try to cover two subtopics at once dilute the signal and create cannibalism problems.</li>
          <li><strong>Build pillar-to-cluster links first, then update as you publish.</strong> When you publish a new cluster page, immediately add a link from the pillar. Do not leave cluster pages as orphans waiting for the next pillar update cycle.</li>
          <li><strong>Match depth to keyword intent.</strong> Cluster pages on informational subtopics should be thorough and educational. Do not thin out cluster pages just because they cover a narrower topic — the word count should match what the searcher needs.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep clusters topically coherent.</strong> Every cluster page should be a genuine subtopic of the pillar. Forcing tangentially related content into a cluster just to build volume weakens the topical signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh the pillar as clusters grow.</strong> The pillar page should be a living document that reflects the cluster. When you add new cluster pages, update the pillar to reference them. This keeps the pillar current and strengthens the hub.</li>
          <li><strong>Track cluster performance as a unit.</strong> Measure organic traffic, rankings, and engagement for the entire cluster, not just individual pages. A cluster's health is measured by how well it performs together.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common topic clustering mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Forgetting to link clusters back to the pillar.</strong> A pillar page that does not receive links from its cluster pages is a hub with no spokes — Google does not recognise the cluster as a network.</li>
          <li><strong>Creating thin cluster pages.</strong> Cluster pages that are 300-word stubs add no topical depth and may be treated as thin content by Google's quality systems. Every cluster page should be the best resource available on its specific subtopic.</li>
          <li><strong>Targeting the same keyword on multiple cluster pages.</strong> If two cluster pages both target "email subject line examples," they will compete against each other. Deduplicate keyword targeting rigorously.</li>
          <li><strong>Building too many clusters at once.</strong> A site with five half-built clusters is weaker than a site with one fully executed cluster. Finish one cluster before starting the next.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring user intent.</strong> The most common structural mistake is building clusters around what the brand wants to talk about rather than what searchers actually want to know. Let keyword research and People Also Ask data drive your cluster structure.</li>
        </ul>

