            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A healthy cluster typically has 5-20 supporting pages per pillar, depending on the breadth of the topic. Start with your most important subtopics and expand the cluster over time. What matters more than the number is that every cluster page has genuine search demand and adds unique value the pillar does not provide.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does topic clustering still work in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes, topic clustering remains one of the most effective content structures for SEO. Google's quality systems continue to reward sites that demonstrate comprehensive topic coverage. The cluster model aligns with how Google evaluates expertise and authority — sites with depth across a subject consistently outrank sites with isolated, disconnected pages.</p></div></div>
          </div>
